/*
===========================================================
TITLE
===========================================================
Copy List with Random Pointer (Deep Copy using HashMap)

===========================================================
PROBLEM STATEMENT
===========================================================
You are given a linked list where each node contains:
• `val`    → the value of the node
• `next`   → pointer to the next node
• `random` → pointer to any node in the list or null

Your task is to create a **deep copy** of this linked list.
The copied list must contain entirely new nodes, such that:
• `next` and `random` pointers of the new list replicate the structure
• No node from the original list is reused

===========================================================
PROBLEM RESOURCE (links)
===========================================================
https://leetcode.com/problems/copy-list-with-random-pointer/

===========================================================
INTUITION
===========================================================
The main difficulty is handling the `random` pointer, because:
• It can point to any node (ahead, behind, or itself)
• During copying, the corresponding copied node may not yet exist

Key idea:
- Use a HashMap to store a mapping:
  Original Node → Copied Node
- This allows us to resolve random pointers easily in a second pass

===========================================================
APPROACH
===========================================================
We solve this problem in **two passes**:

PASS 1: Copy nodes and `next` pointers
------------------------------------
1) Traverse the original list.
2) For each node:
   - Create a new node with the same value.
   - Store mapping: original → copy in a HashMap.
3) Connect copied nodes using `next` pointers.

PASS 2: Copy `random` pointers
-------------------------------
1) Traverse original and copied lists together.
2) For each original node:
   - Set `copied.random = map.get(original.random)`
3) If original.random is null, copied.random automatically becomes null.

===========================================================
EXAMPLE
===========================================================
Original List:
1 → 2 → 3
|    |    |
v    v    v
3    1   null   (random pointers)

Copied List:
1' → 2' → 3'
|     |     |
v     v     v
3'    1'   null

===========================================================
DRY RUN
===========================================================
Input:
1 → 2
random: 1→2, 2→1

First Pass:
map = { 1→1', 2→2' }
Copied next list: 1' → 2'

Second Pass:
1'.random = map.get(1.random) = map.get(2) = 2'
2'.random = map.get(2.random) = map.get(1) = 1'

Output:
Deep copy created correctly.

===========================================================
KEY POINTS
===========================================================
• HashMap enables O(1) access to copied nodes
• Two-pass solution avoids random-pointer dependency issues
• `map.get(null)` safely returns null
• Original list remains unchanged

===========================================================
TIME COMPLEXITY
===========================================================
O(n)
- One traversal to copy nodes
- One traversal to assign random pointers

===========================================================
SPACE COMPLEXITY
===========================================================
O(n)
- Extra space used by HashMap to store node mappings

===========================================================
SPECIAL NOTES FOR LOGIC
===========================================================
• `curr` traverses the original list
• `newCurr` traverses the copied list in parallel
• HashMap ensures correct random pointer mapping
• This is the most intuitive and beginner-friendly approach
===========================================================
*/

/*
// Definition for a Node.
class Node {
    int val;
    Node next;
    Node random;

    public Node(int val) {
        this.val = val;
        this.next = null;
        this.random = null;
    }
}
*/

class Solution {

    public Node copyRandomList(Node head) {

        // HashMap to store mapping:
        // original node -> copied node
        HashMap<Node, Node> map = new HashMap<>();

        Node curr = head;     // Pointer to traverse original list
        Node prev = null;     // Pointer to track previous node in copied list
        Node newHead = null;  // Head of the copied list

        // -------------------------------------------------
        // PASS 1: Create copied nodes and set next pointers
        // -------------------------------------------------
        while (curr != null) {

            // Create a new node with same value as current node
            Node newNode = new Node(curr.val);

            // Store mapping from original node to copied node
            map.put(curr, newNode);

            // If this is the first node, initialize newHead
            if (newHead == null) {
                newHead = newNode;
                prev = newHead;
            } else {
                // Link previous copied node to current copied node
                prev.next = newNode;
                prev = newNode;
            }

            // Move to next node in original list
            curr = curr.next;
        }

        // -------------------------------------------------
        // PASS 2: Assign random pointers using HashMap
        // -------------------------------------------------
        curr = head;           // Reset pointer to original list
        Node newCurr = newHead; // Pointer to traverse copied list

        while (curr != null) {

            // Assign random pointer:
            // map.get(curr.random) gives copied version of random node
            // If curr.random is null, map.get(null) returns null safely
            newCurr.random = map.get(curr.random);

            // Move both pointers forward
            curr = curr.next;
            newCurr = newCurr.next;
        }

        // Return head of deep-copied linked list
        return newHead;
    }
}

